{"title_page": "Evgenia Obraztsova", "text_new": "{{Infobox dancer\n| name          = Evgenia Obraztsova\n| image         = Obraztsova-Covent-Garden.jpg\n| caption       = Obraztsova at the [[Royal Opera House|Royal Opera House in Covent Garden]] in 2009\n| birth_date    = {{birth date and age|1984|1|18|df=y}}\n| birth_place   = [[St. Petersburg]], [[Russia]]\n| education     = [[Vaganova Academy of Russian Ballet|Vaganova School]]\n| occupation    = [[Ballerina]]\n| current_group = [[Mariinsky Theatre]]<br>[[Bolshoi Theatre]]\n| spouse        = Andrey Korobtsov\n}}\n\n'''Evgenia Obraztsova''' ({{lang-ru|\u0415\u0432\u0433\u0435\u043d\u0438\u044f \u041e\u0431\u0440\u0430\u0437\u0446\u043e\u0432\u0430}}; 18 January 1984) is a Russian [[ballerina]]. She is a Prima ballerina with the [[Bolshoi Ballet]] in [[Moscow]], and with the [[Mariinsky Ballet]].<ref name=bolshoi2>{{cite web|url=http://www.bolshoi.ru/en/persons/ballet/|title=Dancers of the Bolshoi Ballet Company|publisher=[[Bolshoi Theatre]]|accessdate=February 2, 2012}}</ref><ref>[http://www.evgeniaobraztsova.com/biography.html Biography]</ref> \n\n==Early life==\nEvgenia Obraztsova was born into a family of dancers, as her mother studied under [[Natalia Dudinskaya]] and was a member of the company at the [[Mikhaylovsky Theatre|Moussorgski Theatre]].  Obraztsova discovered her dance talents early and passed the entrance exams for the [[Vaganova Academy of Russian Ballet|Vaganova School]], which trains young dancers in preparation for joining the Mariinsky troupe. \n\n==Mariinsky ballet==\nEvgenia Obraztsova graduated from the Vaganova Academy in 2002, having studied with Marina Vasilieva, before joining the Mariinsky company and rapidly proceeding through the ranks, protected and guided by a previous ballet star,<ref>\"Kurgapkina is a great teacher. [...] She is wonderful. She always tells me what do with my legs, my face, my hands; and she has taught me a lot about acting.\" (Obraztsova, Evguenia in ''The St. Petersburg Times'', December 16, 2005.</ref> the renowned [[Ninel Kurgapkina]]. Obraztsova soon learned by reading one of the theater brochures that she had been promoted from \"Corps de ballet\" to Coryphee (Ballerina) - no one at the theater had informed her of her promotion.<ref>Normand, ''Ballerina''</ref>\n\nDuring the 2005/2006 season, she continued to advance, and was offered opportunities to dance in three ballets created for her. \n\nIn November, [[Carla Fracci]] (director of the ballet of the [[Rome Opera]]) invited her to perform in ''[[Cinderella (Prokofiev)|Cinderella]].''<ref name=\"ballet-2006\">[http://www.ballet.co.uk/magazines/yr_06/jan06/interview_evgenia_obraztsova.htm Interview: Evgenia Obraztsova, Second Soloist, Kirov Ballet] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110420064637/http://www.ballet.co.uk/magazines/yr_06/jan06/interview_evgenia_obraztsova.htm |date=2011-04-20 }} by Ng, Kevin, Balletco, January 2006.</ref> In March, the leading French choreographer [[Pierre Lacotte]] chose her for the title role in the reconstruction of the ballet [[Ondine (ballet)|Ondine]], and two months later, she returned to Rome to dance in ''Faust'' by Luciano Cannito. \n\nInspired by artists such as [[Diana Vishneva]], [[Ulyana Lopatkina]], and [[Aur\u00e9lie Dupont]], Obrastzova was lauded for creating genuine interpretations, sensitive and intelligent for the key roles.<ref>\"Precocious comparisons with the legendary Galina Ulanova, creator of the role, could be heard, but at least here was a performance driven by spontaneity and freshness, and with plenty of talent for genuine, dramatic effect to boast.\" (Haegeman, Marc in ''Danceview Times'', August 15, 2005).</ref> She was particularly acclaimed for her work in ''[[Romeo and Juliet (Prokofiev)|Romeo and Juliet]]''. \n\n==Soloist==\nIn 2003, Evgenia Obraztsova became the youngest dancer in the history of the Mariinsky to interpret the role of Juliet<ref>\"A natural charmer, she brought beauty and simplicity to the role, coming much closer to a credible portrayal of Juliet, as she convincingly developed from na\u00efve child to passionate and desperate lover.\" (Haegeman, Marc in ''Danceview Times'', August 15, 2005).</ref> and it became one of her favorite roles.<ref>\"As Juliet, the remarkably talented 23-year-old Obraztsova, moved the audience to tears. Dancing with irresistible passion and shimmering lightness, she was Juliet personified, a sweet, gentle girl, innocent yet capable of enduring love. Obraztsova is a deeply emotional and expressive dancer. Her soft, refined movements reflect all shades and subtleties of the sublime music of Prokofiev. Her performance was both beautifully nuanced and technically flawless.\" (Khadarina, Oksana on ''Ballet.co'', January 2007)</ref><ref name=evgenia/>\n\n==Principal dancer with the Bolshoi Ballet==\nEvgenia Obraztsova was promoted to principal dancer with the Bolshoi Ballet in February 2012.<ref>[http://www.bolshoi.ru/en/persons/ballet/899/ Evgenia Obraztsova], website of the Bolchoi theatre.</ref>\n\n==On stage==\nEvgenia Obraztsova is frequently invited as a guest soloist to other countries, and is known for dancing leading roles in ballets such as ''[[Romeo and Juliet (ballet)|Romeo and Juliet]]'', ''[[Ondine (ballet)|Ondine]]'', ''[[Giselle]]'', and ''[[La Sylphide]]''. She has won several awards, including the Gold Medal at the Moscow International Ballet Competition in 2005. Also an actress, she portrayed a ballerina in the 2005 film ''[[Russian Dolls (film)|The Russian Dolls]]'', and was one of the ballerinas profiled in the 2006 documentary ''[[Ballerina (documentary)|Ballerina]]''.<ref name=mariinsky/>\n\nIn high demand, she was again asked to dance the leading role in Vikharev Sergei's ''[[The Awakening of Flora]]'' in 2007. She also participates in numerous tours with the company, whether in Japan, the United States, France, Austria or Israel, as well as several international galas. In 2008 she took the lead role in ''Shurale'', a ballet by Leonid Jakobson. In November 2009, Obraztsova was also invited to the [[Royal Ballet]], dancing as Aurora in their production of ''[[The Sleeping Beauty (ballet)|The Sleeping Beauty]]'',<ref>\"She is all virtue in the part, noble, exquisite in technique, displaying the dance\u2019s brilliancies with unaffected charm, greeting the role as she greets her court with a radiant ease.\" (Crisp, Clement in the [[Financial Times]], November 20, 2009)).</ref> partnered with [[David Makhateli]]. She then danced at the Rome Opera, in ''[[Giselle]]'' in February 2010.<ref name=evgenia/>\n\nAfter ''[[Ondine (ballet)|Ondine]]'', she rejoined Pierre Lacotte in the summer of 2010, replacing [[Isabelle Ciaravola]] for the role of Constance Bonacieux in \"The Three Musketeers\", a newly choreographed production, along with dancers such as [[Mathias Heymann]], [[Mathieu Ganio]], [[Doroth\u00e9e Gilbert]], and [[Marie-Agn\u00e8s Gillot]]. A few months later, she danced again with [[Mathieu Ganio]], and both were invited by the Stanislavsky Theater to dance \"Giselle\" in Moscow.<ref name=evgenia>[http://www.evgeniaobraztsova.com/biography.html Evgenia Obraztsova, the ballerina of Mariinsky theatre] by Farafonova, May on evgeniaobraztsova.com (translated by Kostov, Dmitry).</ref>\n\n==Film Russian Dolls==\nIn 2005, she took a role as an actress in [[C\u00e9dric Klapisch]]'s [[The Russian Dolls]], where she played Natasha. It was a role very close to her actual life, as Natasha was a young ballerina in the Mariinsky Theater.  She never had to audition for the film, and was just noted by chance by Klapisch when he was visiting the Mariinsky.  Obraztsova was also profiled in the 2006 documentary [[Ballerina (2006 film)|''Ballerina'']] by Bertrand Normand, which explored the artistic life of dancers such as [[Ulyana Lopatkina]], [[Svetlana Zakharova (dancer)|Svetlana Zakharova]], and [[Diana Vishneva]].<ref>Normand, ''Ballerina''</ref><ref name=\"ballet-2006\"/>\n\n==Recognition==\nIn 2006, she was named one of [[Dance Magazine's \"25 to Watch\"|\"25 to Watch\"]] by [[Dance Magazine]].<ref>[http://www.dancemagazine.com/issues/January-2006/25-To-Watch 25 To Watch] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120214044637/http://www.dancemagazine.com/issues/January-2006/25-to-Watch |date=2012-02-14 }}  Dance Magazine, January 2006.</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\nEvgenia Obraztsova married sculptor Andrey Korobtsov on 27 April 2014.<ref name=marriage2014>[https://twitter.com/DavidHallberg/status/460387199075512320/photo/1]</ref><ref>[https://twitter.com/ObraztsovaYT/status/460445443663872000]</ref> They have twin daughters, Sofia and Anastasia, born July 25th, 2016.\n\n==Awards==\n* 2002 : M\u00e9daille d'or du Prix Vaganova of Saint Petersburg<ref name=mariinsky>[http://www.mariinsky.ru/en/company/ballet_mt_women/obraztsovaye/ Yevgenia Obraztsova] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110105042050/http://www.mariinsky.ru/en/company/ballet_mt_women/obraztsovaye |date=2011-01-05 }} site of the [[Mariinsky Theatre]].</ref>\n* 2005 : Gold medal at the Moscow International Ballet Competition<ref name=evgenia/><ref name=mariinsky/>\n* 2006 : Prix [[L\u00e9onide Massine]] in Italy\n* 2007 : Masque d'or for best dancer for [[Ondine (ballet)|''Ondine'']] by Pierre Lacotte\n* 2009 : Principal Dancer Prize, ''Esprit de la Danse''\n\n==Repertoire==\n{{columns-list|colwidth=30em|\n* ''[[Ondine (ballet)|Ondine]]'': Ondine<ref name=repertoire>[http://www.evgeniaobraztsova.com/repertoire.html Official site] of Evgenia Obraztsova.</ref>\n* ''[[Romeo and Juliet (Prokofiev)|Romeo and Juliet]]: Juliet\n* ''[[Le Corsaire]]'': trio of Odalisques\n* ''[[Apollon musag\u00e8te]]'': Terpsichore\n* ''[[Sleeping Beauty (Tchaikovsky)|Sleeping Beauty]]'': Princess Aurora\n* ''Le Bourgeois gentilhomme'': Nicole\n* ''[[Don Quixote (ballet)|Don Quixote]]'': Cupid\n* ''[[Carnival of Venice]]'': Colombine\n* ''Shurale'': Siyumbike\n* ''[[The Fountain of Bakhchisarai (ballet)|The Fountain of Bakhchisarai]]'': Marie\n* ''[[La Sylphide]]'': the Sylphide\n* ''La L\u00e9gende de l'amour'': Chirine\n* ''Cendrillon'': Cendrillon\n* ''Le R\u00e9veil de Flore'': Flore\n* ''[[Nutcracker (Tchaikovsky)|Nutcracker]]'': Masha\n* ''[[Swan Lake (Tchaikovsky)|Swan Lake]]'': cygnet,Odette/Odile\n* ''Faust'' : Margherita\n* ''[[Giselle]]'': Giselle\n* ''Le Petit cheval bossu'': the Tsar-Demoiselle\n* ''[[Petrouchka]]'': the Ballerina\n* ''Three Musketeers'': Constance\n* ''Marco Spada'': Angela (The Bandit's Daughter)\n8 ''Legend of Love'' :Princess Shyrin\n}}\n\n==Filmography==\n* ''Don Quixote'', with Olesia Novikova, Leonid Sarafanov, [[Alina Somova]] and other dancers from the Mariinsky Theatre\n* ''Swan Lake'', with Ulyana Lopatkina, Danila Korsuntev, Olesia Novikova and the Mariinsky dancers\n* ''Marco Spada'', with [[David Hallberg]], [[Olga Smirnova (ballet)|Olga Smirnova]], Semyon Chudin, and other dancers from the Bolshoi Ballet\n* ''[[The Russian Dolls]] by [[C\u00e9dric Klapisch]]<ref name=sp>[http://www.sptimes.ru/index.php?action_id=2&story_id=20713 An intimate partnership], by Ng, Kevin, [[St. Petersburg Times]], February 16, 2007.</ref>\n* {{cite video |people=Bertrand Normand (writer/director) |date=2005 |title= Ballerina |url=https://www.imdb.com/name/tt0898897/ |medium=television documentary|language=French, Russian, English |publisher=Adesif Productions |location= France}}<ref name=sp/>\n* ''[[A Frenchman]]'' (2019) as Kira Galkina, ballet dancer of the Bolshoi Theater\n\n==See also==\n* [[List of Russian ballet dancers]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|2}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{Official website|url=http://www.evgeniaobraztsova.com/}} of Evgenia Obraztsova\n* [http://www.bolshoi.ru/en/persons/ballet/899/ Evgenia Obraztsova], on the website of the Bolchoi theatre\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20101223044601/http://deballet.com/artists/yevgenia-obraztsova profile on de Ballet]\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Obraztsova, Evgenia}}\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:1984 births]]\n[[Category:Russian ballerinas]]\n[[Category:People from Saint Petersburg]]\n[[Category:Mariinsky Ballet first soloists]]\n[[Category:Bolshoi Ballet principal dancers]]\n[[Category:Prima ballerinas]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox dancer\n| name          = Evgenia Obraztsova\n| image         = Obraztsova-Covent-Garden.jpg\n| caption       = Obraztsova at the [[Royal Opera House|Royal Opera House in Covent Garden]] in 2009\n| birth_date    = {{birth date and age|1984|1|18|df=y}}\n| birth_place   = [[St. Petersburg]], [[Russia]]\n| education     = [[Vaganova Academy of Russian Ballet|Vaganova School]]\n| occupation    = [[Ballerina]]\n| current_group = [[Mariinsky Theatre]]<br>[[Bolshoi Theatre]]\n| spouse        = Andrey Korobtsov\n}}\n\n'''Evgenia Obraztsova''' ({{lang-ru|\u0415\u0432\u0433\u0435\u043d\u0438\u044f \u041e\u0431\u0440\u0430\u0437\u0446\u043e\u0432\u0430}}; 18 January 1984) is a Russian [[ballerina]]. She is a Prima ballerina with the [[Bolshoi Ballet]] in [[Moscow]], and with the [[Mariinsky Ballet]].<ref name=bolshoi2>{{cite web|url=http://www.bolshoi.ru/en/persons/ballet/|title=Dancers of the Bolshoi Ballet Company|publisher=[[Bolshoi Theatre]]|accessdate=February 2, 2012}}</ref><ref>[http://www.evgeniaobraztsova.com/biography.html Biography]</ref> \n\n==Early life==\nEvgenia Obraztsova was born into a family of dancers, as her mother studied under [[Natalia Dudinskaya]] and was a member of the company at the [[Mikhaylovsky Theatre|Moussorgski Theatre]].  Obraztsova discovered her dance talents early and passed the entrance exams for the [[Vaganova Academy of Russian Ballet|Vaganova School]], which trains young dancers in preparation for joining the Mariinsky troupe. \n\n==Mariinsky ballet==\nEvgenia Obraztsova graduated from the Vaganova Academy in 2002, having studied with Marina Vasilieva, before joining the Mariinsky company and rapidly proceeding through the ranks, protected and guided by a previous ballet star,<ref>\"Kurgapkina is a great teacher. [...] She is wonderful. She always tells me what do with my legs, my face, my hands; and she has taught me a lot about acting.\" (Obraztsova, Evguenia in ''The St. Petersburg Times'', December 16, 2005.</ref> the renowned [[Ninel Kurgapkina]]. Obraztsova soon learned by reading one of the theater brochures that she had been promoted from \"Corps de ballet\" to Coryphee (Ballerina) - no one at the theater had informed her of her promotion.<ref>Normand, ''Ballerina''</ref>\n\nDuring the 2005/2006 season, she continued to advance, and was offered opportunities to dance in three ballets created for her. \n\nIn November, [[Carla Fracci]] (director of the ballet of the [[Rome Opera]]) invited her to perform in ''[[Cinderella (Prokofiev)|Cinderella]].''<ref name=\"ballet-2006\">[http://www.ballet.co.uk/magazines/yr_06/jan06/interview_evgenia_obraztsova.htm Interview: Evgenia Obraztsova, Second Soloist, Kirov Ballet] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110420064637/http://www.ballet.co.uk/magazines/yr_06/jan06/interview_evgenia_obraztsova.htm |date=2011-04-20 }} by Ng, Kevin, Balletco, January 2006.</ref> In March, the leading French choreographer [[Pierre Lacotte]] chose her for the title role in the reconstruction of the ballet [[Ondine (ballet)|Ondine]], and two months later, she returned to Rome to dance in ''Faust'' by Luciano Cannito. \n\nInspired by artists such as [[Diana Vishneva]], [[Ulyana Lopatkina]], and [[Aur\u00e9lie Dupont]], Obrastzova was lauded for creating genuine interpretations, sensitive and intelligent for the key roles.<ref>\"Precocious comparisons with the legendary Galina Ulanova, creator of the role, could be heard, but at least here was a performance driven by spontaneity and freshness, and with plenty of talent for genuine, dramatic effect to boast.\" (Haegeman, Marc in ''Danceview Times'', August 15, 2005).</ref> She was particularly acclaimed for her work in ''[[Romeo and Juliet (Prokofiev)|Romeo and Juliet]]''. \n\n==Soloist==\nIn 2003, Evgenia Obraztsova became the youngest dancer in the history of the Mariinsky to interpret the role of Juliet<ref>\"A natural charmer, she brought beauty and simplicity to the role, coming much closer to a credible portrayal of Juliet, as she convincingly developed from na\u00efve child to passionate and desperate lover.\" (Haegeman, Marc in ''Danceview Times'', August 15, 2005).</ref> and it became one of her favorite roles.<ref>\"As Juliet, the remarkably talented 23-year-old Obraztsova, moved the audience to tears. Dancing with irresistible passion and shimmering lightness, she was Juliet personified, a sweet, gentle girl, innocent yet capable of enduring love. Obraztsova is a deeply emotional and expressive dancer. Her soft, refined movements reflect all shades and subtleties of the sublime music of Prokofiev. Her performance was both beautifully nuanced and technically flawless.\" (Khadarina, Oksana on ''Ballet.co'', January 2007)</ref><ref name=evgenia/>\n\n==Principal dancer with the Bolshoi Ballet==\nEvgenia Obraztsova was promoted to principal dancer with the Bolshoi Ballet in February 2012.<ref>[http://www.bolshoi.ru/en/persons/ballet/899/ Evgenia Obraztsova], website of the Bolchoi theatre.</ref>\n\n==On stage==\nEvgenia Obraztsova is frequently invited as a guest soloist to other countries, and is known for dancing leading roles in ballets such as ''[[Romeo and Juliet (ballet)|Romeo and Juliet]]'', ''[[Ondine (ballet)|Ondine]]'', ''[[Giselle]]'', and ''[[La Sylphide]]''. She has won several awards, including the Gold Medal at the Moscow International Ballet Competition in 2005. Also an actress, she portrayed a ballerina in the 2005 film ''[[Russian Dolls (film)|The Russian Dolls]]'', and was one of the ballerinas profiled in the 2006 documentary ''[[Ballerina (documentary)|Ballerina]]''.<ref name=mariinsky/>\n\nIn high demand, she was again asked to dance the leading role in Vikharev Sergei's ''[[The Awakening of Flora]]'' in 2007. She also participates in numerous tours with the company, whether in Japan, the United States, France, Austria or Israel, as well as several international galas. In 2008 she took the lead role in ''Shurale'', a ballet by Leonid Jakobson. In November 2009, Obraztsova was also invited to the [[Royal Ballet]], dancing as Aurora in their production of ''[[The Sleeping Beauty (ballet)|The Sleeping Beauty]]'',<ref>\"She is all virtue in the part, noble, exquisite in technique, displaying the dance\u2019s brilliancies with unaffected charm, greeting the role as she greets her court with a radiant ease.\" (Crisp, Clement in the [[Financial Times]], November 20, 2009)).</ref> partnered with [[David Makhateli]]. She then danced at the Rome Opera, in ''[[Giselle]]'' in February 2010.<ref name=evgenia/>\n\nAfter ''[[Ondine (ballet)|Ondine]]'', she rejoined Pierre Lacotte in the summer of 2010, replacing [[Isabelle Ciaravola]] for the role of Constance Bonacieux in \"The Three Musketeers\", a newly choreographed production, along with dancers such as [[Mathias Heymann]], [[Mathieu Ganio]], [[Doroth\u00e9e Gilbert]], and [[Marie-Agn\u00e8s Gillot]]. A few months later, she danced again with [[Mathieu Ganio]], and both were invited by the Stanislavsky Theater to dance \"Giselle\" in Moscow.<ref name=evgenia>[http://www.evgeniaobraztsova.com/biography.html Evgenia Obraztsova, the ballerina of Mariinsky theatre] by Farafonova, May on evgeniaobraztsova.com (translated by Kostov, Dmitry).</ref>\n\n==Film Russian Dolls==\nIn 2005, she took a role as an actress in [[C\u00e9dric Klapisch]]'s [[The Russian Dolls]], where she played Natasha. It was a role very close to her actual life, as Natasha was a young ballerina in the Mariinsky Theater.  She never had to audition for the film, and was just noted by chance by Klapisch when he was visiting the Mariinsky.  Obraztsova was also profiled in the 2006 documentary [[Ballerina (2006 film)|''Ballerina'']] by Bertrand Normand, which explored the artistic life of dancers such as [[Ulyana Lopatkina]], [[Svetlana Zakharova (dancer)|Svetlana Zakharova]], and [[Diana Vishneva]].<ref>Normand, ''Ballerina''</ref><ref name=\"ballet-2006\"/>\n\n==Recognition==\nIn 2006, she was named one of [[Dance Magazine's \"25 to Watch\"|\"25 to Watch\"]] by [[Dance Magazine]].<ref>[http://www.dancemagazine.com/issues/January-2006/25-To-Watch 25 To Watch] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120214044637/http://www.dancemagazine.com/issues/January-2006/25-to-Watch |date=2012-02-14 }}  Dance Magazine, January 2006.</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\nEvgenia Obraztsova married sculptor Andrey Korobtsov on 27 April 2014.<ref name=marriage2014>[https://twitter.com/DavidHallberg/status/460387199075512320/photo/1]</ref><ref>[https://twitter.com/ObraztsovaYT/status/460445443663872000]</ref> They have twin daughters, Sofia and Anastasia, born July 25th, 2016.\n\n==Awards==\n* 2002 : M\u00e9daille d'or du Prix Vaganova of Saint Petersburg<ref name=mariinsky>[http://www.mariinsky.ru/en/company/ballet_mt_women/obraztsovaye/ Yevgenia Obraztsova] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110105042050/http://www.mariinsky.ru/en/company/ballet_mt_women/obraztsovaye |date=2011-01-05 }} site of the [[Mariinsky Theatre]].</ref>\n* 2005 : Gold medal at the Moscow International Ballet Competition<ref name=evgenia/><ref name=mariinsky/>\n* 2006 : Prix [[L\u00e9onide Massine]] in Italy\n* 2007 : Masque d'or for best dancer for [[Ondine (ballet)|''Ondine'']] by Pierre Lacotte\n* 2009 : Principal Dancer Prize, ''Esprit de la Danse''\n\n==Repertoire==\n{{columns-list|colwidth=30em|\n* ''[[Ondine (ballet)|Ondine]]'': Ondine<ref name=repertoire>[http://www.evgeniaobraztsova.com/repertoire.html Official site] of Evgenia Obraztsova.</ref>\n* ''[[Romeo and Juliet (Prokofiev)|Romeo and Juliet]]: Juliet\n* ''[[Le Corsaire]]'': trio of Odalisques\n* ''[[Apollon musag\u00e8te]]'': Terpsichore\n* ''[[Sleeping Beauty (Tchaikovsky)|Sleeping Beauty]]'': Princess Aurora\n* ''Le Bourgeois gentilhomme'': Nicole\n* ''[[Don Quixote (ballet)|Don Quixote]]'': Cupid\n* ''[[Carnival of Venice]]'': Colombine\n* ''Shurale'': Siyumbike\n* ''[[The Fountain of Bakhchisarai (ballet)|The Fountain of Bakhchisarai]]'': Marie\n* ''[[La Sylphide]]'': the Sylphide\n* ''La L\u00e9gende de l'amour'': Chirine\n* ''Cendrillon'': Cendrillon\n* ''Le R\u00e9veil de Flore'': Flore\n* ''[[Nutcracker (Tchaikovsky)|Nutcracker]]'': Masha\n* ''[[Swan Lake (Tchaikovsky)|Swan Lake]]'': cygnet,Odette/Odile\n* ''Faust'' : Margherita\n* ''[[Giselle]]'': Giselle\n* ''Le Petit cheval bossu'': the Tsar-Demoiselle\n* ''[[Petrouchka]]'': the Ballerina\n* ''Three Musketeers'': Constance\n* ''Marco Spada'': Angela (The Bandit's Daughter)\n8 ''Legend of Love'' :Princess Shyrin\n}}\n\n==Filmography==\n* ''Don Quixote'', with Olesia Novikova, Leonid Sarafanov, [[Alina Somova]] and other dancers from the Mariinsky Theatre\n* ''Swan Lake'', with Ulyana Lopatkina, Danila Korsuntev, Olesia Novikova and the Mariinsky dancers\n* ''Marco Spada'', with [[David Hallberg]], [[Olga Smirnova (ballet)|Olga Smirnova]], Semyon Chudin, and other dancers from the Bolshoi Ballet\n* ''[[The Russian Dolls]] by [[C\u00e9dric Klapisch]]<ref name=sp>[http://www.sptimes.ru/index.php?action_id=2&story_id=20713 An intimate partnership], by Ng, Kevin, [[St. Petersburg Times]], February 16, 2007.</ref>\n* {{cite video |people=Bertrand Normand (writer/director) |date=2005 |title= Ballerina |url=https://www.imdb.com/name/tt0898897/ |medium=television documentary|language=French, Russian, English |publisher=Adesif Productions |location= France}}<ref name=sp/>\n\n==See also==\n* [[List of Russian ballet dancers]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|2}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{Official website|url=http://www.evgeniaobraztsova.com/}} of Evgenia Obraztsova\n* [http://www.bolshoi.ru/en/persons/ballet/899/ Evgenia Obraztsova], on the website of the Bolchoi theatre\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20101223044601/http://deballet.com/artists/yevgenia-obraztsova profile on de Ballet]\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Obraztsova, Evgenia}}\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:1984 births]]\n[[Category:Russian ballerinas]]\n[[Category:People from Saint Petersburg]]\n[[Category:Mariinsky Ballet first soloists]]\n[[Category:Bolshoi Ballet principal dancers]]\n[[Category:Prima ballerinas]]\n", "name_user": "Gerarus", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eFilmography:complement", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Evgenia_Obraztsova"}
{"title_page": "Brick Train", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=January 2016}}\n{{Use British English|date=January 2016}}\n\n{{Infobox artwork\n|title=Brick Train\n|image_file=Brick_Train_Darlington_-_geograph.org.uk_-_308862.jpg\n|coordinates={{coord|54|31|24|N |1|29|53|W|display=inline,title}}\n|city=[[Darlington]], [[County Durham]], England\n|artist=[[David Mach]]\n|completion_date=1997\n|type=[[Sculpture]]\n|material=[[Brick]]\n|subject=[[Steam locomotive]]\n|pushpin_map=County Durham\n\n}}\nThe '''''Brick Train''''' is a [[brick]] [[sculpture]] located on the outskirts of the town of [[Darlington]], in the English county of [[County Durham|Durham]]. The sculpture was created by [[David Mach]] in 1997 to celebrate the town's railway heritage, and is modelled on the [[steam locomotive]] [[LNER Class A4 4468 Mallard|''Mallard'']], which set a UK rail speed record of {{convert|126|mph}} in 1938. The locomotive is depicted as if just having exited a tunnel, with the billowing smoke typical of such an exit.<ref name=dbttid>{{cite web |url=http://www.thisisdarlington.com/attractions/Darlingtons_Brick_Train.asp |title=Darlington\u2019s Brick Train |publisher=This is Darlington |accessdate=6 January 2020 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20200106115338/http://www.thisisdarlington.com/attractions/Darlingtons_Brick_Train.asp |archivedate=6 January 2020 |url-status=live}}</ref><ref name=dbtctabbc>{{cite news |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-england-tees-40356417 |title=Darlington Brick Train celebrates 20th anniversary |date=23 June 2017 |work=BBC News |publisher=[[BBC]] |accessdate=6 January 2020}}</ref>\n\nThe sculpture is situated adjacent to [[Morrisons]] supermarket in the Morton Park shopping area to the east of Darlington town and in the civil parish of [[Morton Palms]]. A total of 185,000 [[Accrington brick|Accrington Nori brick]]s were used in the sculpture's construction, and it is {{convert|7|m}} high and {{convert|29|m}} long, covering an area of {{convert|600|m2}}. It is hollow inside and special bricks provide gaps that enable [[bat]]s to fly inside and roost. The sculpture is visible from the nearby [[A66 road]], and was officially unveiled by [[Peter Palumbo, Baron Palumbo|Lord Palumbo of Walbrook]] on 23 June 1997.<ref name=dbttid/><ref name=dbtctabbc/><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.bing.com/maps/?mkt=en-gb&v=2&cp=54.523361~-1.498028&lvl=14&sp=Point.54.523361_-1.498028_Brick%20Train&sty=s |title=Brick Train |work=Bing Maps |publisher=[[Ordnance Survey]] |accessdate=6 January 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.lancashiretelegraph.co.uk/news/6177023.spotters-go-bats-brick-train/ |title=Spotters go bats over a brick train |work=Lancashire Telegraph |date=26 June 1997 |accessdate=7 January 2020 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20200107135447/https://www.lancashiretelegraph.co.uk/news/6177023.spotters-go-bats-brick-train/ |archivedate=7 January 2020 |url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nThe work cost [[Pound sterling|\u00a3]]760,000, which was provided by the [[National Lottery Heritage Fund]] along with smaller contributions from [[Darlington Borough Council]], [[Northern Arts]] and Morrisons.<ref name=dbtctabbc/>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n[[Category:Buildings and structures in the Borough of Darlington]]\n[[Category:Culture in County Durham]]\n[[Category:Darlington]]\n[[Category:Outdoor sculptures in England]]\n[[Category:1997 sculptures]]\n[[Category:1997 establishments in England]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=January 2016}}\n{{Use British English|date=January 2016}}\n\n{{Infobox artwork\n|title=Brick Train\n|image_file=Brick_Train_Darlington_-_geograph.org.uk_-_308862.jpg\n|coordinates={{coord|54|31|24|N |1|29|53|W|display=inline,title}}\n|city=[[Darlington]], [[County Durham]], England\n|artist=[[David Mach]]\n|completion_date=1997\n|type=[[Sculpture]]\n|material=[[Brick]]\n|subject=[[Steam locomotive]]\n|pushpin_map=County Durham\n\n}}\nThe '''''Brick Train''''' is a [[brick]] [[sculpture]] located on the outskirts of the town of [[Darlington]], in the English county of [[County Durham|Durham]]. The scuplture was created by [[David Mach]] in 1997 to celebrate the town's railway heritage, and is modelled on the [[steam locomotive]] [[LNER Class A4 4468 Mallard|''Mallard'']], which set a UK rail speed record of {{convert|126|mph}} in 1938. The locomotive is depicted as if just having exited a tunnel, with the billowing smoke typical of such an exit.<ref name=dbttid>{{cite web |url=http://www.thisisdarlington.com/attractions/Darlingtons_Brick_Train.asp |title=Darlington\u2019s Brick Train |publisher=This is Darlington |accessdate=6 January 2020 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20200106115338/http://www.thisisdarlington.com/attractions/Darlingtons_Brick_Train.asp |archivedate=6 January 2020 |url-status=live}}</ref><ref name=dbtctabbc>{{cite news |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-england-tees-40356417 |title=Darlington Brick Train celebrates 20th anniversary |date=23 June 2017 |work=BBC News |publisher=[[BBC]] |accessdate=6 January 2020}}</ref>\n\nThe sculpture is situated adjacent to [[Morrisons]] supermarket in the Morton Park shopping area to the east of Darlington town and in the civil parish of [[Morton Palms]]. A total of 185,000 [[Accrington brick|Accrington Nori brick]]s were used in the sculpture's construction, and it is {{convert|7|m}} high and {{convert|29|m}} long, covering an area of {{convert|600|m2}}. It is hollow inside and special bricks provide gaps that enable [[bat]]s to fly inside and roost. The sculpture is visible from the nearby [[A66 road]], and was officially unveiled by [[Peter Palumbo, Baron Palumbo|Lord Palumbo of Walbrook]] on 23 June 1997.<ref name=dbttid/><ref name=dbtctabbc/><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.bing.com/maps/?mkt=en-gb&v=2&cp=54.523361~-1.498028&lvl=14&sp=Point.54.523361_-1.498028_Brick%20Train&sty=s |title=Brick Train |work=Bing Maps |publisher=[[Ordnance Survey]] |accessdate=6 January 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.lancashiretelegraph.co.uk/news/6177023.spotters-go-bats-brick-train/ |title=Spotters go bats over a brick train |work=Lancashire Telegraph |date=26 June 1997 |accessdate=7 January 2020 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20200107135447/https://www.lancashiretelegraph.co.uk/news/6177023.spotters-go-bats-brick-train/ |archivedate=7 January 2020 |url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nThe work cost [[Pound sterling|\u00a3]]760,000, which was provided by the [[National Lottery Heritage Fund]] along with smaller contributions from [[Darlington Borough Council]], [[Northern Arts]] and Morrisons.<ref name=dbtctabbc/> \n\n==References==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n[[Category:Buildings and structures in the Borough of Darlington]]\n[[Category:Culture in County Durham]]\n[[Category:Darlington]]\n[[Category:Outdoor sculptures in England]]\n[[Category:1997 sculptures]]\n[[Category:1997 establishments in England]]\n", "name_user": "John of Reading", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200etop:Typo/generalfixes, replaced: scuplture \u2192 sculpture", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Brick_Train"}
